<div class="textblock"><p>Best practices for designing the Main Menu for your Freemium games.</p>
<h1><a class="anchor" id="mm_intro"></a>
Main Menu Design</h1>
<p>Main Menu best practices are critically important to your game. A great Main Menu makes a great first impression and sets the tone of quality and ease-of-use for your game.</p>
<p>An effective and inviting Main Menu maximizes your opportunity to convert your player into a paying customer, and can be the difference between a good game and a great game’s financial performance.</p>
<p>Overall, your Main Menu should be thoughtfully designed and use appealing visuals to welcome the player to your game.</p>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_UI_elements"></a>
Quality art and UI elements</h2>
<p>Beautiful and interesting game art should be used to set the tone of what is to come and to get the player excited to play.</p>
<p>Buttons that are integrated into the art, and match the look and feel of the game, make for a cohesive and engaging Main Menu. When possible, use in-game art or UI elements as buttons instead of plain text or text boxes.</p>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_effective_designs"></a>
Effective designs</h2>
<p>A great main menu will offer no barriers to entry and provide no room for confusion.</p>
<p><b>Grim Tales: The Wishes Collector’s Edition</b></p>
<div class="image">
<img src="mm_grim_tales.png" alt="mm_grim_tales.png"/>
</div>
<ul>
<li>Buttons are well-integrated with the scene. The <b>Unlock Now!</b> button is eye-catching and unique.</li>
<li>Smoke flows from chimney, the fire flickers and reflects in water, and fog rolls through the scene.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Ghost Towns: The Cats of Ulthar Collector’s Edition</b></p>
<div class="image">
<img src="mm_ghost_towns.png" alt="mm_ghost_towns.png"/>
</div>
<ul>
<li>Button style matches the scenery and character well.</li>
<li>The boy’s eyes blink and his chest heaves.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Beauty &amp; the Beast: Mystery Legends Collector’s Edition</b></p>
<div class="image">
<img src="mm_B_B_updated.png" alt="mm_B_B_updated.png"/>
</div>
<ul>
<li>Button style matches theme and scenery well.</li>
<li>Snow falling, bright glow under and around the <b>Unlock Now!</b> button.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Not as good</b>: Avoid unnecessary clutter. Simplicity increases the clarity of the message to, “Play our game! Unlock our game!” Players should easily find and tap on the button they want.</p>
<div class="image">
<img src="mm_Houseof1000doors_oldmenu.png" alt="mm_Houseof1000doors_oldmenu.png"/>
</div>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_movement"></a>
Movement on the Main Menu</h2>
<p>View the following games on a device to compare effective designs.</p>
<p><b>Beauty &amp; the Beast: Mystery Legends Collector’s Edition</b></p>
<p>Some of the best Main Menus begin with a quick zoom in or out on a scene before the buttons appear.</p>
<div class="image">
<img src="mm_bb_1.png" alt="mm_bb_1.png"/>
</div>
<div class="image">
<img src="mm_bb_2.png" alt="mm_bb_2.png"/>
</div>
<p><b>Mystery Case Files: Return to Ravenhearst Collector’s Edition</b></p>
<p>You can introduce the Main Menu by first presenting a series of enticing, evocative images.</p>
<div class="image">
<img src="mm_r2r_1.png" alt="mm_r2r_1.png"/>
</div>
<div class="image">
<img src="mm_r2r_2.png" alt="mm_r2r_2.png"/>
</div>
<p><b>Love Chronicles: The Spell Collector’s Edition</b></p>
<p>Falling snow, rustling leaves, character movements (breathing, blinking, etc.), flashing lights, and waving flags are examples of movement that can be added to an otherwise static Main Menu.</p>
<div class="image">
<img src="mm_1_love_chronicles.png" alt="mm_1_love_chronicles.png"/>
</div>
<h1><a class="anchor" id="mm_layout"></a>
Main Menu Elements</h1>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="GDN"></a>
Game Discovery Network</h2>
<p>The Game Discovery Network (GDN) is a promotional dashboard that loads before a game begins. The GDN enables Big Fish to promote and cross-sell other games within the Big Fish network. This promotion boosts new games and increases the audience across the network. GDN behavior is controlled by Big Fish via an internal server after launch.</p>
<div class="image">
<img src="GDNexample.png" alt="GDNexample.png"/>
</div>
<p>After a user pauses the game, the dashboard enters a Pause/Resume mode. This mode provides buttons to resume the game and to link back to the Main Menu. The Pause/Resume menu should appear after 1 hour if the game has been inactive, whenever the device sleeps, or Fast App Switching occurs. No additional code is needed to create or initialize this view, and display of this view will be handled automatically by the <a class="el" href="interfacebfg_manager.html" title="Initialize the Big Fish Game Components. ">bfgManager</a>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Use the <b><a class="el" href="interfacebfg_manager.html" title="Initialize the Big Fish Game Components. ">bfgManager</a></b> class in the Big Fish iOS SDK to implement the GDN.</li>
<li>Integrate the GDN in all builds.</li>
<li>Customize the icons for your game in the <b>bfgpromodashboard_gamespecific.zip</b> file within the <b>bfg_gamespecific_resources</b> directory in your project resources directory.</li>
<li>The GDN background should be a customized blue watermark specific to your game. This asset is pulled from the Xcode project <b>Launch Images</b> setting under the Summary section.<ul>
<li>The GDN will use these images for iPad only. The iPhone will always be plain blue.</li>
<li>You can create these assets yourself, or Big Fish will provide these assets if you contact your Big Fish Producer.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Add code to navigate to the Main Menu from the resume mode after the button sends the Main Menu notification: <a class="el" href="bfg_manager_8h.html#ab1124a3783ef12de91333c8f44d9522f">BFGPROMODASHBOARD_NOTIFICATION_MAINMENU</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Also see <a class="el" href="reference_class.html#gdn_bfgManager">bfgManager and the Game Discovery Network</a>.</p>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_ads"></a>
Big Fish ad integration</h2>
<p>Ads allow Big Fish to promote and cross-sell within each game, and Big Fish will determine the appropriate content. Ads can be targeted by device type, screen resolution, and game. Big Fish controls ads via an internal server after the game has launched.</p>
<p>The <a class="el" href="interfacebfg_manager.html" title="Initialize the Big Fish Game Components. ">bfgManager</a> downloads ad packages and displays individual ads on a periodic basis. Games include an initial embedded ad package. The SDK sends instructions with each ad package about when to check next for an updated ad package. When that time comes, the client downloads the current package for the device, resolution, and game, and then begins cycling through the ads.</p>
<p>There are two Big Fish ads sizes:</p>
<ul>
<li>iPad - 768x75</li>
<li>iPhone 4 and up - 640x100</li>
</ul>
<p>The device type will be detected so that the correct ad size is shown, including for Universal SKUs.</p>
<ul>
<li>Use the [<a href="interfacebfg_manager.html#a27b8f441980c2ad13de2bb20d6746903" class="el">bfgManager startAds</a>] and [<a href="interfacebfg_manager.html#a12b90710348a0f4fe2284b5c372433d8" class="el">bfgManager stopsAds</a>] API to integrate ads.</li>
<li>Include room at the top or bottom of the game's Main Menu for ads to be displayed.The Big Fish ads banners may be positioned centered at the bottom or top of the Main Menu. These are controlled by Big Fish via a server and will update dynamically throughout the life of the game.</li>
</ul>
<p>Also see <a class="el" href="reference_class.html#ads_bfgManager">Ads - bfgManager startAds/stopAds and bfgAdsController</a>.</p>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_unlock"></a>
Unlock Now! button</h2>
<p>The <b>Unlock Now!</b> button should be the most eye-catching element on the Main Menu. It should be labelled <b>Unlock Now!</b> with no exceptions.</p>
<ul>
<li>The <b>Unlock Now!</b> button opens the Buy Wall screen when pressed. For more information on the Buy Wall upsell, see <a class="el" href="buy_wall.html">Fremium Buy Wall Best Practices</a>.</li>
<li>The <b>Unlock Now!</b> button should be more prominent than all other buttons, including the <b>Play</b> button.</li>
<li>Make it as easy as possible for a user to unlock the game.</li>
<li>Recommended: Use a glint, shine, or other animation to draw attention to this button.</li>
</ul>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_play"></a>
Play button</h2>
<p>The <b>Play</b> button is the second most prominent and eye-catching element on the Main Menu. This button should be labelled <b>Play</b>, with no exceptions.</p>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_Login"></a>
Sign In button</h2>
<p>Big Fish Login is an interface that lets users sign in to their Big Fish accounts inside a Big Fish app. Call [<a href="interfacebfg_login_controller.html#a5ea88a700c4b6280c35f1b60b1f68a88" class="el">bfgLoginController isLoggedIn</a>] to determine whether to show <b>Sign In</b> or <b>Sign Out</b>. You can get a fully formed UIButton from the SDK or build your own button out of images also provided by the SDK.</p>
<dl class="section note"><dt>Note</dt><dd><ul>
<li>Login is an optional feature. Discuss with your Big Fish Producer whether you should implement Big Fish Login in your game, and where to place the <b>Sign In/Sign Out</b> buttons.</li>
<li>The Options sub-menu may be an ideal place for Sign In/Sign Out.</li>
<li>You are responsible for adding the Sign In button to your view hierarchy.</li>
</ul>
</dd></dl>
<p>Also see <a class="el" href="reference_class.html#rc_bfgLogin">Big Fish Login</a>.</p>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_rating"></a>
Rating buttons</h2>
<p>Ratings buttons engage the user to evaluate games. There are four types you can use to prompt the user for reviews and other feedback:</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Main Menu rating prompt:</b> Appears after the user pauses and resumes game play. May have the same dimensions as the <b>iSplash Newsletter</b> button and <b>More Games</b> button.</li>
<li><b>In-game rating prompt:</b> Appears at strategic points in the game's progress.</li>
<li><b>Like [Game Title]?:</b> Launches a pop-up. May appear at the end of a game session, after the user pauses and resumes game play, or on the Sneak Peek pop-up. If there is no planned sequel for your game, then the rating button should read: <b>Like [Game Title]?</b></li>
<li><b>Sneak Peek:</b> Launches a pop-up. May appear on the Main Menu when the user first accesses it, or when the user returns to the game after a pause. Has a Rating button for currently active game.</li>
</ul>
<p>The <a class="el" href="interfacebfg_rating.html" title="Enables users to rate games. ">bfgRating</a> class implements game rating. The <a class="el" href="interfacebfg_game_reporting.html" title="Required game logging APIs. ">bfgGameReporting</a> class has several events that track this feature.</p>
<p>Also see <a class="el" href="reference_class.html#rc_bfgRating">Rating - bfgRating</a>.</p>
<h3><a class="anchor" id="ratings_json"></a>
bfg_default_settings.json ratings settings</h3>
<p>For a generic game rating notification, use the rating keys in the <b>bfg_default_settings.json</b> file copied from the <b>bfglib_gamespecific_resources</b> directory.</p>
<p>In <b>bfg_default_settings.json</b>, values can be set for the <b>rating_days_until_prompt</b> and <b>rating_uses_until</b> prompt parameters. These should be left at the default unless you are directed otherwise by your Big Fish Producer. The ratings prompt appears after the set number of days or game uses, regardless of the progress within the game. Prompts based on these parameters will not display in active games until the user returns to the Main Menu, or the user removes the game from the multi-tasking tray.</p>
<h3><a class="anchor" id="Main_menu_rating"></a>
Main Menu rating prompt</h3>
<p>The Main Menu rating prompt encourages users to rate a game. Tapping the button from the Main Menu displays a pop-up promoting the user to rate the game.</p>
<ul>
<li>Use the [<a href="interfacebfg_rating.html#ada82cbb76d090204f6bd5305e75aa501" class="el">bfgRating canShowMainMenuRateButton</a>] API to display this button.</li>
<li>You <em>must</em> create the pop-up for the rating prompt, and you <em>must</em> provide the art assets for the button and pop-up. Submit those assets to your Big Fish Producer for approval.</li>
<li>Call the Big Fish [<a href="interfacebfg_rating.html#ad284cb377269073f1182867c4c82fbdb" class="el">bfgRating mainMenuRateApp</a>] API to navigate the user to the correct iTunes page to rate your app.</li>
</ul>
<p>For more information on implementing the rating prompt, see the <a class="el" href="interfacebfg_rating.html" title="Enables users to rate games. ">bfgRating</a> class reference.</p>
<h3><a class="anchor" id="In_game_rating"></a>
In-game rating prompt</h3>
<p>The in-game rating prompt appears at a natural point in the game via a UIAlert, based on the completion of game levels or mini-games, or after a few scenes in a hidden object game.</p>
<ul>
<li>Set the <b>rating_significant_events_until_prompt</b> key in <b>bfg_default_settings.json</b> to the number of significant events that must be triggered before the game displays the in-game ratings prompt.</li>
<li>For Freemium games, display the first ratings prompt before the end of the free trial. The best recommended position is at the end of the second-to-last level, scene, or mini-game before the free trial ends and the player is presented with the Buy Wall.</li>
</ul>
<dl class="section note"><dt>Note</dt><dd>Make sure that this does not display over the Buy Wall.<br/>
</dd></dl>
<div class="image">
<img src="ratingnotification.jpg" alt="ratingnotification.jpg"/>
</div>
<p>The rating provides the following options:</p>
<ul>
<li><b>Rate <em style="color:red">game_name</em></b> takes the user to the App Store to rate the game. The in-game rating prompt and Main Menu rating prompt stop appearing.</li>
<li><b>Remind me later</b> reminds the user again at another point in the game.</li>
<li><b>No thank you!</b> sets a flag that stops rating prompts from appearing.</li>
</ul>
<h3><a class="anchor" id="mm_enjoying"></a>
Like [Game Title]? pop-up</h3>
<p>If the <b>Like [Game Title]?</b> button is tapped, a pop-up with content from the current game should appear.</p>
<div class="image">
<img src="likegame_popup_new.jpg" alt="likegame_popup_new.jpg"/>
</div>
<ul>
<li><b>Rotating screenshots of the current game that the player has not yet seen from <em>AFTER</em> the Buy Wall:</b> These could appear as rotating screenshots in a rectangle, as in the example above, or as a series of screenshots that expand when tapped.</li>
<li><b>“Enjoying [Current Game Title]?”:</b> This should be the full title, including Collector’s Edition if applicable, but not including HD.</li>
<li><b>“Let us know, rate it now!”:</b> This sentence can be in all caps or lower case.</li>
<li><b>“Rate it Now!” button:</b> When tapped, the button will call the [<a href="interfacebfg_rating.html#ad284cb377269073f1182867c4c82fbdb" class="el">bfgRating mainMenuRateApp</a>] API, and take the player directly to the App Store to rate the game or write a review. Once this button is tapped, it should no longer appear on the Main Menu.</li>
<li>An <b>"X"</b> button in the top right corner should also be included to close the pop-up.</li>
</ul>
<h3><a class="anchor" id="mm_popup"></a>
Sneak Peek pop-up</h3>
<p>If your game has a sequel that has already been released or is currently in production, then you will need a <b>Sneak Peek</b> button. This button should have "Sneak Peek" displayed on top (check for correct spelling), followed by the sequel game title, and should include art from the sequel.</p>
<div class="image">
<img src="sneakpeek_button.png" alt="sneakpeek_button.png"/>
</div>
<p>When the <b>Sneak Peek</b> button is tapped, a pop-up with sequel content should appear: <b>Sneak Peek: [Sequel Game Title]</b></p>
<dl class="section note"><dt>Note</dt><dd>If your Sneak Peak requires localization, contact your Big Fish Producer for access to the General Locs on the Big Fish external FTP site. For more information, see <a class="el" href="standards.html#devResourcesFtpSite">Developer Resources FTP Site</a>.</dd></dl>
<div class="image">
<img src="sneakpeek_new.jpg" alt="sneakpeek_new.jpg"/>
</div>
<ul>
<li><b>Sequel game title:</b> This should be the full title, including Collector’s Edition if applicable, but not including HD.</li>
<li><b>Rotating screenshots of the sequel game:</b> These could appear as rotating screenshots in a rectangle, as in the example above, or as a series of screenshots that expand when tapped.</li>
<li><b>“Enjoying [Current Game Title]?”:</b> This can be a shortened title.</li>
<li><b>“Rate it now in anticipation of the sequel!”:</b> This sentence can be in all caps or lower case.</li>
<li><b>“Rate it Now!” button:</b> When tapped, the button will call the [<a href="interfacebfg_rating.html#ad284cb377269073f1182867c4c82fbdb" class="el">bfgRating mainMenuRateApp</a>] API, and take the player directly to the App Store to rate the game or write a review. Once this button is tapped, it should no longer appear on the Main Menu.</li>
<li>An <b>"X"</b> button in the top right corner should also be included to close the pop-up.</li>
</ul>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_ce"></a>
Collector's Edition Bonus/Extras button</h2>
<p>All Collector's Edition games should have a <b>Bonus</b> or <b>Extras</b> button containing all Collector's Edition content for the game.</p>
<ul>
<li>This additional content is unlocked when the player completes the In-App Purchase for Full Game Unlock.</li>
<li>Before completing this In-App Purchase, when the player tries to access this content before Full Game Unlock, the player is directed to the Buy Wall upsell. For more information, see <a class="el" href="buy_wall.html">Fremium Buy Wall Best Practices</a>.</li>
</ul>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_more_games"></a>
More Games button</h2>
<p>All games <em>must</em> include a <b>More Games</b> button on the Main Menu.</p>
<ul>
<li>Calls the [<a href="interfacebfg_manager.html#a0f7b15d1862eaca88de68a9f48a6d8a8" class="el">bfgManager showMoreGames</a>] API when a user taps the <b>More Games</b> button.</li>
<li>Launches a More Games UI that looks similar to the GDN's pause/resume menu.</li>
<li>The Big Fish logo should be visible on the <b>More Games</b> button, but otherwise the style of this button should match the Main Menu style.</li>
<li>Ask your Big Fish Producer for the most up-to-date logo assets when you are ready to create this button.</li>
</ul>
<p>Also see <a class="el" href="reference_class.html#more_games_bfgManager">More Games - bfgManager showMoreGames</a>.</p>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_isplash"></a>
iSplash! Newsletter button</h2>
<p>All games must contain an <b>iSplash! Newsletter</b> button on the Main Menu. Tapping this button opens an e-mail message for subscribing to the newsletter.</p>
<div class="image">
<img src="iSplash.png" alt="iSplash.png"/>
</div>
<ul>
<li>Use the <b><a class="el" href="interfacebfg_splash.html" title="API for iSplash newsletter functionality. ">bfgSplash</a></b> class to implement the iSplash! newsletter.</li>
<li>The button images are generated on the fly for the current device. UIImage objects can be retrieved from [<a href="interfacebfg_splash.html#ab7774b060090a63d6476c18ec7a69bbd" class="el">bfgSplash splashMenuImageNormal</a>] and [<a href="interfacebfg_splash.html#a60470100ae8df10958edb8fdc2c35623" class="el">bfgSplash splashMenuImageHighlighted</a>]. Button image sizes are iPhone: 117x64 pts; iPad: 195x105 pts. <b>Note:</b> Image sizes are measured in points, not pixels. All iSplash! images have a scale of 2.0 (retina).</li>
<li>Alternatively, a fully functional UIButton that is configured to send the email and hide itself is available via [<a href="interfacebfg_splash.html#a21075bdca2b97cb891e911a7de2e0290" class="el">bfgSplash createSplashButton</a>].</li>
<li>Games that support both landscape and portrait orientations must provide a button for both orientations.</li>
<li>Display the button only to non-subscribers, according to the value returned by the [<a href="interfacebfg_splash.html#ae7ac46eae890c5c07e130c9640a48022" class="el">bfgSplash getNewsletterSent</a>] API.</li>
<li>Tapping the button calls the [<a href="interfacebfg_splash.html#a4a9564739b6a607cb6ad6f4527cd5b7a" class="el">bfgSplash displayNewsletter</a>] API. This opens a pre-filled iSplash e-mail message that the user may send to subscribe to the newsletter. The e-mail includes the Bundle ID for the game and the BFGUDID for the device.</li>
<li>After the user sends the newsletter subscription e-mail, update the UI to reflect the new subscriber status.</li>
</ul>
<dl class="section note"><dt>Note</dt><dd>You can register for the <a class="el" href="bfg_splash_8h.html#a128708b81aed0a102a1649ede1bbf778">BFGSPLASH_NOTIFICATION_COMPLETED</a> notification to respond to that event in your application.</dd></dl>
<p>Also see <a class="el" href="reference_class.html#rc_iSplash">iSplash! Newsletter - bfgSplash</a>.</p>
<h1><a class="anchor" id="mm_options"></a>
Options sub-menu</h1>
<p>In addition to the game options/settings, there are several required Big Fish elements that should be included on this sub-menu.</p>
<p>For information on implementing this feature, see <a class="el" href="reference_class.html#rc_options_submenu_bfgManager">bfgManager and the Options sub-menu</a>.</p>
<p>Here is an example from the iPad release of <em>Penny Dreadfuls: Sweeney Todd Collector's Edition</em> with all required elements.</p>
<div class="image">
<img src="pennydreadoptions.png" alt="pennydreadoptions.png"/>
</div>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_support"></a>
Support button</h2>
<p>All games <em>must</em> include a <b>Support</b> button in the Options sub-menu. Tapping the <b>Support</b> button opens a Web browser in the game that displays a mobile games help article on <a href="http://bigfishgames.custhelp.com/app/home" class="el" target="_blank">bigfishgames.com</a>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Add the <b>Support</b> button in the style of your game and call the [<a href="interfacebfg_manager.html#a36dc0bd019902e9cf816c926e66bf8f0" class="el">bfgManager showSupport</a>] API.</li>
</ul>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_privacy_policy"></a>
Privacy Policy button</h2>
<p>All games <em>must</em> include a <b>Privacy Policy</b> button in the Options sub-menu. Tapping the <b>Privacy Policy</b> button opens a Web browser in the game that displays the full Privacy Policy on <a href="http://www.bigfishgames.com/company/privacy.html" class="el" target="_blank">bigfishgames.com</a>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Add the <b>Privacy Policy</b> button in the style of your game and call the [<a href="interfacebfg_manager.html#ace61025e839f1298ebc3c78307dd3791" class="el">bfgManager showPrivacy</a>] API.</li>
</ul>
<dl class="section note"><dt>Note</dt><dd>This API launches a localized version of the Privacy Policy page. Games without a localized version should use the English version (e.g., Russian or Chinese).</dd></dl>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_terms_use"></a>
Terms of Use button</h2>
<p>All games <em>must</em> include a <b>Terms of Use</b> button in the Options sub-menu. Tapping the <b>Terms of Use</b> button opens a Web browser in the game that displays the full Terms of Use on <a href="http://www.bigfishgames.com/company/terms.html" class="el" target="_blank">bigfishgames.com</a>.</p>
<ul>
<li>Add the <b>Terms of Use</b> button in the style of your game and call the [<a href="interfacebfg_manager.html#a8e7c1a2dab58d6921c67cef2fdb6b130" class="el">bfgManager showTerms</a>] API.</li>
</ul>
<dl class="section note"><dt>Note</dt><dd>This API launches a localized version of the Terms of Use page. Games without a localized version should use the English version (e.g., Russian or Chinese).</dd></dl>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_copyright_legal"></a>
Copyright and legal text</h2>
<p>All games <em>must</em> include the default copyright for the current calendar year. Big Fish franchise games and owned intellectual property must also include trademarks for the game or franchise.</p>
<ul>
<li>Default copyright text:</li>
</ul>
 
    <table border=1 cellspacing=0><tr>
        <td>&copy;2014 Big Fish Games, Inc. Big Fish, and the Big Fish logo are trademarks of Big Fish Games, Inc.
            Version Number <i style=color:red>XX.XX.XX</i></td></tr></table>
<ul>
<li>Example of copyright text for a franchise game or owned intellectual property:</li>
</ul>
 
    <table border=1 cellspacing=0><tr>
        <td>&copy;2014 Big Fish Games, Inc. Big Fish, the Big Fish logo, and &lt;Franchise Name or Game Name&gt; are trademarks of Big Fish Games, Inc.
Version Number<i style=color:red>XX.XX.XX</i></td></tr></table>
<ul>
<li>Replace <i style=color:red>XX.XX.XX</i>  with the current build version number. For more information about build version numbers, see <a class="el" href="production.html#Versioning">Versioning</a>.</li>
</ul>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_credits"></a>
Credits</h2>
<p>Credits for your game are optional. For Big Fish Studios titles only, contact your Big Fish Producer to see if you must include Big Fish credits.</p>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_sliders"></a>
Sound sliders</h2>
<p>All sound sliders should conform to Apple guidelines and default to 70%. For more information, see the <a class="el" href="f2p_usability.html#usability_audio">Audio</a> usability requirements.</p>
<h2><a class="anchor" id="mm_tell_a_friend"></a>
Tell A Friend button</h2>
<p>All games <em>must</em> provide a <b>Tell A Friend</b> button on the Options sub-menu. It should match the appearance of the other buttons and the overall look of your game.</p>
<p>All games <em>must</em> use the [<a href="interfacebfg_manager.html#a3fd48676ed5f795ed26a0ff856e4ec79" class="el">bfgManager canShowTellAFriendButton</a>] API to determine if they should show the <b>Tell A Friend</b> button on the Options sub-menu. When the button is clicked, the [<a class="el" href="interfacebfg_manager.html" title="Initialize the Big Fish Game Components. ">bfgManager</a> <a href="interfacebfg_manager.html#abc88f8458fff6d3934f4bd6ec9b0c11c" class="el">showTellAFriend</a>] API should be called to display the e-mail. </p>
